track_notes:
This route is described in Gillean Dafferns Kananaskis Country Trail guide, vol 5. 
It starts with fording the Highwood River at the Sentinel Day Use Area, just west of where Cataract Creek enters the Highwood. The river was knee-deep at the end of July when we did the trip. The hike is delightful along the west bank of Cataract creek, below bands of cliffs. There are single track trails leading to the summit, sometimes clear and well-defined, sometimes braided and uncertain.
There is cell-phone service on the summit.

The east side of Mount Mann has several cliff bands that make it difficult to find a route through. On descent follow the most obvious path leading down. It heads due south and suddenly turns NE and provides a clear, well-defined descent path that is a lot shorter than the ascent route. It would be a good route of ascent, but at the bottom the path braids and it would be difficult to find the place to leave the path along the stream.

If you are not willing to brave the Highwood river in the winter, this is a fun snowshoe outing that avoids the main river crossing. You start by hiking along the riverbed for a few kilometers until you approach the large cutblocks that you can use to ascend to the col. From the col, follow the ridge to Mount Mann.
